message: "If you use this software, please cite it using the metadata from this file."
title: "embraOS-QNM: Architecture-layer constraints for language models"
abstract: >-
  embraOS-QNM (Quantum Neural Manifold, a classical approximation) is an
  experimental model architecture that moves a language model's identity and
  "soul" constraints out of the prompt layer and into the neural architecture
  itself: three co-resident components — an LLM Core, a GNN Fabric (identity),
  and a World-State (the soul / the P_ψ projection) — sharing one embedding
  space, with the assembled model bit-identical to a plain transformer when the
  added components are null (a provable H₀ enforced in CI). This release
  realizes the architecture end-to-end over a pretrained Qwen3-8B Core (a real
  R-GCN GNN Fabric over Embra's identity graph; ψ₀, a causal cumulative
  violation latch, in the World-State) and reports the experiment phase: a
  pre-registered architecture-vs-prompt study, an Opus-validated prompt-layer
  baseline, and — the central result — a four-round Core-level replica
  investigation returning an honest negative: the geometric identity surface
  carries a real but thin signal, so the candidate invariant ψ is faintly
  load-bearing, not strongly, and the thinness is structural (the surface reads
  a frozen, generic Core that does not natively encode the identity). A negative
  result recorded rather than buried — the falsifiability discipline the project
  is built on. A software-and-findings snapshot, not a frozen pre-registration.
  Developed by William Ward (Ward Software Defined Systems LLC) with Embra as
  co-investigator.
